32
00:02:17,198 --> 00:02:20,059
Your clan's relationships with the neighboring clans

33
00:02:20,480 --> 00:02:22,741
is as important as any economic resources.

34
00:02:23,750 --> 00:02:29,595
You can go to war, but unlike civilization, you definitely cannot conquer all your neighbors.

35
00:02:31,056 --> 00:02:36,680
What you do instead is influence your relations with them, for example, by sending an emissary

36
00:02:36,720 --> 00:02:41,464
with a dialogue there, and equally importantly, with story decisions.

37
00:02:43,225 --> 00:02:46,627
The game tracks a lot of different relationships between clans.

38
00:02:47,728 --> 00:02:52,011
One of the key things, I think, is that favors are one of the currencies of the game.

39
00:02:55,308 --> 00:02:59,291
So as a book, there are over 400 interactive scenes.

40
00:02:59,351 --> 00:03:00,652
There's three of them shown there.

41
00:03:00,672 --> 00:03:04,776
The scenes usually have four or five responses.

42
00:03:06,477 --> 00:03:08,039
It's not choose your own adventure, though.

43
00:03:08,059 --> 00:03:10,841
In the interactive fiction lingo,

44
00:03:11,141 --> 00:03:14,264
it's probably a floating module.

45
00:03:15,565 --> 00:03:19,068
There is no single line that goes through the entire story.

46
00:03:20,809 --> 00:03:23,391
But these floating modules do connect.

47
00:03:24,550 --> 00:03:26,971
largely through the political and economic model

48
00:03:28,291 --> 00:03:29,091
and we'll also

49
00:03:29,772 --> 00:03:31,092
try to have as much intention

50
00:03:31,832 --> 00:03:34,313
to these as we can. For example, we might choose

51
00:03:34,333 --> 00:03:38,735
a particular clan to intensify the stakes of a situation.

52
00:03:40,975 --> 00:03:45,817
These scenes can also end up with multi-year storylines.

53
00:03:46,897 --> 00:03:50,538
For example, you may have a chance to see those rootless riders in the center

54
00:03:50,599 --> 00:03:51,899
again, depending on how you treat them.

55
00:03:54,884 --> 00:04:01,912
And we try to draw the entire story to a dramatic and emotionally satisfying conclusion.

56
00:04:04,215 --> 00:04:10,402
So the game has about as many words as the first four Harry Potter novels, but not all

57
00:04:10,443 --> 00:04:10,963
in a row.

58
00:04:11,964 --> 00:04:15,168
It's got a lot of repeatability and there's a lot of variation.

59
00:04:18,357 --> 00:04:21,198
We set the story in the world of Glorantha.

60
00:04:21,378 --> 00:04:24,779
This is a extremely detailed and realistic world,

61
00:04:25,319 --> 00:04:27,360
and it helps us have an immersive background.

62
00:04:27,380 --> 00:04:30,201
You can sort of think of it almost like a character

63
00:04:30,241 --> 00:04:33,582
in the story, like Hogwarts is in the Harry Potter stories.

64
00:04:34,962 --> 00:04:39,363
Glorantha is a complete world with a mythology and cultures.

65
00:04:39,523 --> 00:04:41,484
It's sort of as if our background was already

66
00:04:41,544 --> 00:04:42,224
play-tested.

67
00:04:43,224 --> 00:04:44,745
And the late Greg Stafford began writing

68
00:04:44,785 --> 00:04:46,465
about Glorantha over 50 years ago.

69
00:04:48,080 --> 00:04:51,221
I'm picturing there the 800-page guide to Glorantha,

70
00:04:51,661 --> 00:04:54,202
which is over 6.3 kilograms of information,

71
00:04:54,262 --> 00:04:55,722
or 14 pounds if you're American.

72
00:04:56,602 --> 00:04:59,623
But we actually sort of play in the spaces between that,

73
00:05:00,263 --> 00:05:02,783
extrapolating from kind of just a few paragraphs in that.

74
00:05:05,564 --> 00:05:09,045
The setting gives us the main conflict in the game,

75
00:05:09,105 --> 00:05:11,885
which is that the main god of your neighbors

76
00:05:12,045 --> 00:05:13,005
killed your main god,

77
00:05:13,646 --> 00:05:15,346
and that's what set in place your migration.

78
00:05:16,663 --> 00:05:20,767
It also gives us a pantheon of deities, which provide magic.

79
00:05:21,047 --> 00:05:25,730
This impacts the economic model, including combat.

80
00:05:27,191 --> 00:05:30,073
But we try to make magic more than just sort of something

81
00:05:30,134 --> 00:05:30,674
mechanical.

82
00:05:30,754 --> 00:05:33,356
It's not always going to be, well, you get plus 2 in combat.

83
00:05:33,396 --> 00:05:35,938
We try to make it feel like magic.

84
00:05:36,058 --> 00:05:38,099
And that means it needs to have a much fuzzier feel.

85
00:05:39,610 --> 00:05:47,298
One of the best examples of that is that we have the ability to let the player enter the

86
00:05:47,338 --> 00:05:53,164
world of mythology, cross over to the other side, and play through a myth.

87
00:05:54,165 --> 00:05:56,728
They reenact the stories of the god, and they get magic.

88
00:05:57,449 --> 00:05:59,751
And the outcome of this is usually quite fuzzy.

89
00:05:59,771 --> 00:06:01,933
You're basically making your own story.

90
00:06:02,873 --> 00:06:06,714
And if you've actually played King of Dragon Pass, these are

91
00:06:06,734 --> 00:06:09,555
sort of the myths that you know from the King of Dragon

92
00:06:09,575 --> 00:06:10,855
Pass days well in the future.

93
00:06:13,256 --> 00:06:15,956
The goal of all of this is to make an immersive experience.

94
00:06:16,817 --> 00:06:19,477
Sort of the summary of this is I want you to be playing the

95
00:06:19,557 --> 00:06:21,018
story, not the game.

96
00:06:21,898 --> 00:06:24,218
And just a quick reminder that just because it's largely

97
00:06:24,258 --> 00:06:27,059
text-based does not mean it's not immersive.

98
00:06:31,257 --> 00:06:36,599
Our approach to immersion is that we try to make the player know what someone in the world

99
00:06:36,659 --> 00:06:39,840
knows and not have gamey things intrude on that.

100
00:06:41,101 --> 00:06:45,202
One of the things we have to do is introduce you to what you would know if you're in the

101
00:06:45,242 --> 00:06:45,542
world.

102
00:06:46,343 --> 00:06:52,605
And we start off with a clan questionnaire, which helps introduce the history of your

103
00:06:52,665 --> 00:06:52,965
clan.

104
00:06:54,072 --> 00:06:57,734
It's not a show, don't tell, but it's a do, don't show.

105
00:06:58,635 --> 00:07:00,476
So we can avoid an expository lump.

106
00:07:00,796 --> 00:07:03,878
And this also makes your clan's back story the

107
00:07:03,918 --> 00:07:04,779
player's back story.

108
00:07:06,179 --> 00:07:08,481
It's sort of like character creation in a lot of games.

109
00:07:09,341 --> 00:07:12,603
And it does not only initialize the story situations

110
00:07:12,643 --> 00:07:15,745
you're putting your clan into, but some of the economic model

111
00:07:15,805 --> 00:07:16,105
as well.

112
00:07:19,035 --> 00:07:24,357
The problem is that the players are probably not members of the writer culture and we don't

113
00:07:24,377 --> 00:07:28,079
want to penalize them because they don't know as much as someone in the world would know.

114
00:07:29,039 --> 00:07:32,380
So the solution is to have advisors.

115
00:07:33,121 --> 00:07:37,342
These are leaders that will basically have three roles in the game.

116
00:07:38,343 --> 00:07:39,603
They'll provide information.

117
00:07:40,204 --> 00:07:41,884
They also act as your playing pieces.

118
00:07:42,825 --> 00:07:47,327
And they have their own personalities and become sympathetic characters, which helps

119
00:07:47,487 --> 00:07:48,307
enhance immersion.

120
00:07:49,801 --> 00:07:54,306
Because the advisors are so key, the player gets to choose them from a pool of leaders.

121
00:07:56,328 --> 00:08:01,714
So advisors will give in-world information about, like, the state of the economy and

122
00:08:01,734 --> 00:08:02,495
the relationships.

123
00:08:04,137 --> 00:08:09,123
They'll recommend actions, and they'll also remind you to do things that you would do

124
00:08:09,223 --> 00:08:10,684
if you're running a clan.

125
00:08:14,617 --> 00:08:20,182
As the game progresses, your advisors will get older and eventually die of old age.

126
00:08:22,645 --> 00:08:28,871
They have skills which are used to overcome obstacles and also relate to the kind of advice

127
00:08:28,931 --> 00:08:29,311
you give.

128
00:08:29,932 --> 00:08:33,355
For example here, Ave 2 is heroic and magic, so...

129
00:08:34,462 --> 00:08:39,062
She would probably be someone to listen to if she's talking about magic, but if she's

130
00:08:39,102 --> 00:08:43,443
talking about a diplomatic situation where she has only a fair skill, you might want

131
00:08:43,463 --> 00:08:45,123
to listen to one of your other advisors.

132
00:08:47,684 --> 00:08:49,604
Advisors all have personalities.

133
00:08:51,184 --> 00:08:55,445
We – and their advice, as you can see, can sometimes reflect that personality.

134
00:08:56,245 --> 00:09:01,106
We do try to prioritize skill-based advice on the assumption that that's what the player

135
00:09:01,186 --> 00:09:03,027
needs in order to succeed.

136
00:09:09,069 --> 00:09:12,533
So to give advisors personalities, there's 33

137
00:09:13,094 --> 00:09:14,575
personality traits in the game.

138
00:09:15,997 --> 00:09:18,340
They are randomly generated.

139
00:09:19,902 --> 00:09:22,965
Every advisor has only two personality traits, which is

140
00:09:23,005 --> 00:09:25,228
kind of pretty limiting for humans.

141
00:09:25,288 --> 00:09:27,811
But we want to make sure that over the course of the game,

142
00:09:28,351 --> 00:09:29,613
they can be noticed by a player.

143
00:09:31,560 --> 00:09:35,964
Some of the traits are contradictory, so we make sure that when we randomly generate them,

144
00:09:36,324 --> 00:09:38,446
a character gets only something that makes sense.

145
00:09:38,566 --> 00:09:43,951
You can't be both optimistic and pessimistic, at least not within the scope of this simulation.

146
00:09:45,152 --> 00:09:51,878
And while a character's religion is not actually a personality trait, that also fits into the

147
00:09:52,278 --> 00:09:53,339
valid combinations.

148
00:09:54,120 --> 00:09:58,243
If you worship the war god, you're not going to have a personality trait of peaceful.

149
00:10:00,622 --> 00:10:03,583
So why do we have personality in the game?

150
00:10:03,703 --> 00:10:06,564
Well, as I mentioned before, it drives advice.

151
00:10:07,424 --> 00:10:09,345
But more importantly, it'll drive action.

152
00:10:10,245 --> 00:10:13,446
Your advisors are people with their own personalities and

153
00:10:13,486 --> 00:10:14,266
their own agendas.

154
00:10:15,167 --> 00:10:17,287
And they'll go off and do things on their own without

155
00:10:17,327 --> 00:10:19,388
you asking them or even wanting them to.

156
00:10:20,808 --> 00:10:25,210
So we try to be fair to the player and only have something

157
00:10:25,250 --> 00:10:28,551
like this happen after you had a chance to witness their

158
00:10:28,571 --> 00:10:29,211
personality.

159
00:10:30,282 --> 00:10:33,965
And if it's visible at the bottom, you can see a little bit of script that a character

160
00:10:34,005 --> 00:10:40,630
has to be on the clan council for at least two years before this scene will show up where

161
00:10:40,650 --> 00:10:45,434
the goat fan starts inviting people in and you, the player, have to deal with the situation.

162
00:10:47,376 --> 00:10:49,537
Personality can also be a positive thing.

163
00:10:49,557 --> 00:10:52,359
It can be a modifier in many situations.

164
00:10:52,780 --> 00:10:58,264
Or you wouldn't send a merciful character or a peaceful character off to intimidate

165
00:10:58,304 --> 00:10:58,764
someone else.

166
00:11:00,205 --> 00:11:01,526
you might send your harsh character.

167
00:11:05,389 --> 00:11:09,553
So advisors being people sometimes have conflicts with each other.

168
00:11:09,573 --> 00:11:15,619
The situation here, one of your advisors has told the buzzard people they should try harder

169
00:11:15,639 --> 00:11:21,724
to fit in, and another one is reminding him that the correct term is not buzzard people

170
00:11:21,784 --> 00:11:22,525
but adoptees.

171
00:11:23,799 --> 00:11:26,420
I think in the game, some of the best writing is in advice.

172
00:11:26,920 --> 00:11:30,482
And that's probably because it allows us to have a viewpoint

173
00:11:31,322 --> 00:11:33,603
instead of just presenting facts, like we

174
00:11:33,623 --> 00:11:34,923
have 12 cows less.

175
00:11:38,385 --> 00:11:41,786
So let's look behind the scene at how strategy and

176
00:11:41,846 --> 00:11:42,826
story work together.

177
00:11:44,431 --> 00:11:47,712
We have our own domain-specific language.

178
00:11:48,393 --> 00:11:49,873
I called it the Opal Scripting Language,

179
00:11:49,973 --> 00:11:52,054
after an old code name for King of Dragon Pass.

180
00:11:52,834 --> 00:11:54,215
It's a domain-specific language,

181
00:11:54,295 --> 00:11:56,856
and it was kind of designed around something

182
00:11:56,876 --> 00:11:59,797
that would be easy for our writer to use.

183
00:12:02,698 --> 00:12:05,339
At the top there is a conditional response.

