00:14:44,036 --> 00:14:44,736
certain time limit.

233
00:14:47,841 --> 00:14:51,044
One difference between Six Ages and a lot of games is that

234
00:14:51,284 --> 00:14:52,946
we'll only show relevant items.

235
00:14:53,286 --> 00:14:56,369
And that's because you're someone in the world, and you

236
00:14:56,389 --> 00:14:57,631
don't really know what might have been.

237
00:14:57,651 --> 00:15:00,353
If only you had more clan magic, you could have drawn

238
00:15:00,393 --> 00:15:03,276
on it, but it's not something you would even consider.

239
00:15:03,296 --> 00:15:06,739
There's no might, what might have been.

240
00:15:09,341 --> 00:15:13,864
The scenes are managed in a scene queue, which is a priority queue.

241
00:15:14,485 --> 00:15:17,447
The granularity is a turn, because we're a turn-based strategy game.

242
00:15:18,487 --> 00:15:24,612
And this is basically how we can add time to the narrative and handle those long storylines.

243
00:15:31,612 --> 00:15:35,192
Because something may change once you've triggered

244
00:15:35,212 --> 00:15:37,613
something in the future, the character that it relates to

